Part 5: Why Don't We Use the Entire Dataset at Once?

You might ask:

"Why not use all 10,000 samples together?"

Problem 1: Memory Limitation

Large datasets cannot fit into GPU memory.

Modern datasets:

ImageNet → 1.2 million images.
LLM datasets → billions of tokens.

Processing everything together would require enormous hardware.

Problem 2: Slow Updates

If we wait for the whole dataset before updating the weights, learning becomes slow.

Mini-batches allow the model to update itself frequently.

Part 6: Types of Training Based on Batch Size
1. Batch Gradient Descent
Batch size = Entire dataset.
One update after processing all samples.
1000 samples
      ↓
Compute loss
      ↓
Update weights once
Advantages
Stable updates.
Smooth convergence.
Disadvantages
Slow.
Requires lots of memory.
2. Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)
Batch size = 1.
Sample 1 → Update
Sample 2 → Update
Sample 3 → Update
...
Advantages
Very fast updates.
Escapes local minima more easily.
Disadvantages
Noisy learning.
Loss fluctuates heavily.
3. Mini-Batch Gradient Descent ⭐ (Industry Standard)

Typical batch sizes:

16, 32, 64, 128, 256

This balances:

Speed,
Memory usage,
Stability.

Almost every modern deep learning model uses mini-batch training.

Part 7: What is Learning Rate?
Definition

The learning rate determines how much the model changes its weights after each update.

You already learned yesterday that backpropagation computes gradients. The learning rate controls how strongly we react to those gradients.

Think of it as the step size during learning.

Mountain Analogy

Imagine climbing down a mountain in dense fog to reach the lowest valley.

Case 1: Tiny Steps
Step size = very small
Safe.
Stable.
But it takes forever to reach the bottom.
Case 2: Huge Steps
Step size = very large
You may jump over the valley.
You may bounce back and forth.
You might never settle.
Case 3: Balanced Steps
Step size = moderate
Progress is steady.
Reaches the minimum efficiently.

The learning rate is exactly this step size.

