Part 9: Interaction Between Batch Size and Learning Rate

These two are closely related.

Batch Size	Typical Behavior
Small (16-32)	Noisier gradients, often generalizes better
Medium (64-128)	Balanced
Large (512+)	Stable gradients, but may require larger learning rates
Intuition

A larger batch gives a more accurate estimate of the "true direction" for weight updates.

A smaller batch is like asking only a few people for advice—it is noisier but often surprisingly effective.

Part 10: Hyperparameters vs Parameters

This distinction is very important for interviews.

Parameters

These are learned automatically:

Weights.
Biases.

Example:

W = 0.45
b = -1.23

The neural network discovers these values during training.

Hyperparameters

These are chosen before training starts.

Examples:

Learning rate.
Batch size.
Number of epochs.
Number of hidden layers.
Number of neurons per layer.

You, the engineer, decide these values.

Interview Definition

Parameters are learned from data; hyperparameters are set by the engineer before training.

