Part 13: Simulating Epochs
data = list(range(1, 11))
epochs = 3

for epoch in range(epochs):
    print(f"\nEpoch {epoch+1}")
    
    for sample in data:
        print(f"Processing sample {sample}")

The same dataset is processed multiple times—exactly what epochs mean.

Part 14: How PyTorch Uses These Concepts

When you train a model in PyTorch:

from torch.utils.data import DataLoader

train_loader = DataLoader(
    dataset=train_dataset,
    batch_size=32,
    shuffle=True
)

epochs = 10

for epoch in range(epochs):
    for batch in train_loader:
        # Forward pass
        # Compute loss
        # Backward pass
        # Update weights
        pass

Here:

batch_size=32 → each iteration uses 32 samples.
epochs=10 → entire dataset repeated 10 times.
The optimizer internally uses the chosen learning rate.
Part 15: Real Industry Values
Application	Batch Size	Learning Rate	Epochs
Small ML dataset	16–64	0.01	20–100
CNN image classification	32–256	0.001	10–50
NLP Transformer fine-tuning	8–32	2e-5 to 5e-5	2–5
Large Language Model pretraining	Thousands (distributed)	Dynamically scheduled	Millions of iterations

Notice that engineers don't simply increase epochs forever—they monitor validation loss and stop when performance stops improving.

